explanation: GENERIC_IO_CONST_DATA_CAST: This macro is used on the 'buffer' argument passed to write(). To assess const-qualification you must see whether the macro removes const (casts away const) or preserves it. write (prototype): The const-qualification of the write() buffer parameter (some platforms use 'const void *', others 'void *') determines whether the cast in GENERIC_IO_CONST_DATA_CAST is needed and whether const is being discarded. OS_impl_file_internal_record_t: The function reads impl->selectable and impl->fd; the struct definition shows the types involved and whether any accessed members are pointers whose const-qualification matters. OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: This macro produces 'impl' from *token; its definition may dereference or otherwise use the token and could require token to be non-const. OS_SelectSingle_Impl (prototype): Called with 'token' (const OS_object_token_t *) — its parameter types determine whether passing a const pointer to it is compatible or whether const is effectively discarded by the call. OS_ObjectIndexFromToken (prototype): OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET likely expands to or uses this; its parameter types and constness are relevant to determine whether token's const qualification is preserved. OS_stream_state constants (OS_STREAM_STATE_WRITABLE): Needed to understand the bitmask checks and whether 'operation' is used in ways that could affect const-correctness (e.g., passed by pointer to functions that might modify it). OS_object_token_t (type definition): To evaluate whether the pointer parameter 'const OS_object_token_t *token' is appropriately const-qualified, the definition of the pointed-to type is required (e.g., if it contains mutable pointers or is used by macros/functions that expect non-const).
